In article <1993Jan14.032341.1507@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:
|
|In response to Christopher Browne, TeX is not a standard in the
|mathematical world, though it may be in the West among Unix systems.
|In particular, there's no reason to believe Sidelnikov can read TeX.
|As one who has been taken to task by others for allegedly being
|U.S.-centric, I'm surprised others should make this error.
|
|Those who make this an occasion to attack me personally are simply not
|taking this discussion seriously, but are being partisan.
|
|As for what I'd prefer, as one of the authors of Fortran II and IV at
|IBM in the '50s, I'd prefer Fortran. More importantly, in my many
|visits to Soviet computer centers I found Fortran very widespread
|there even now, and the likelihood of Sidelnikov or his people being
|able to read Fortran is rather better than that they can read TeX.
|Some of the centers I'm intimately familiar with include those of the
|principal Science and Energy advisors to Gorbachev when he was running
|things, and thus they might be typical of well-funded centers there.
|
